## OIDC / JWT (B.8.12 â€” b8-12-e2e-migration)

<!-- Audit: B.8.12 (b8-12-e2e-migration) -->

`security-policy.yaml` lands the deferred Envoy-OIDC wiring (ADR-B87-006 â†’
ADR-B812-002). In Envoy Gateway **v1.8** the JWT provider config is folded into
the `SecurityPolicy` resource (`spec.jwt.providers[]`) â€” there is **no separate
JWTAuthn resource** (CARRY-4, verified LIVE; evidence.md P-40). The policy:

- targets the `<project-name>-backend-route` `HTTPRoute` (`spec.targetRef`);
- declares one JWT provider `zitadel` with `issuer: https://<zitadel-issuer>`
  (the Zitadel `ExternalDomain` from `infra/zitadel/values-forge.yaml.tmpl`,
  cross-ref **identity.yaml@1.1.0**: chart `10.0.2`, appVersion `v4.14.0`);
- fetches signing keys via `remoteJWKS.backendRefs` â†’ a companion `Backend`
  resource pointing at the Zitadel host. The jwks path is
  `<issuer>/oauth/v2/keys` (CARRY-2, live-confirmed from the discovery doc;
  evidence.md P-38).

Defense-in-depth: the backend ALSO re-validates the JWT in-process via the
`jwt-authorizer` tower layer (`backend/crates/grpc-api/src/jwt_middleware.rs.tmpl`,
CARRY-3 / evidence.md P-39), so in-cluster S2S calls that bypass the gateway are
still checked. The S2S Connect client (`transport_connect_client.rs.tmpl`)
presents the Zitadel machine-user Bearer token validated by both layers.

> Audiences (`<zitadel-client-id>`) and any EG-patch-specific `remoteJWKS`
> field shape carry `VERIFY-AT-DEPLOY` markers â€” confirm against your Zitadel
> project + your EG v1.8.x build at deploy. No API string is fabricated.

## Coexistence with Kong (additive-first)

Both gateways converge on `<project-name>-backend` (`fsm-backend`, http port
8080). B.8.4 adds Envoy **in parallel**; it does not touch
`infra/kong/kong.yml.example.tmpl`. The route-cutover/canary mechanism is
B.8.10; Kong removal + the actual 1.0.0 â†’ 2.0.0 bump is B.8.14. Transport is
Connect/gRPC-Web pass-through at the gateway (ADR-B84-006) â€” any RESTâ†”gRPC
transcoding decision belongs to B.8.6.
